Each instance of Molecule is a microscopic-scale object whose component atoms are all chemically bonded to each other; typically, this means that the atoms are covalently bonded. Examples: some instances of Molecule, including molecules of oxygen (O2), ozone (O3), water (H2O), carbon monoxide (CO), carbon dioxide (CO2), etc., contain covalently bonded atoms belonging to the collection Oxygen. comment:
An instance of RelationTypeByLogicalFeature (q.v.) and a specialization of AtLeastPartiallyCommutativeRelation. Each instance of PartiallyCommutativeRelation PARTCOMRELN is a predicate or function that is commutative in some, but not all, of its argument-places (see commutativeInArgs). More precisely, suppose for example that PARTCOMRELN is a predicate (function) that is commutative only in its odd-numbered argument-places, and that PARTCOMRELN holds among (has the value VAL for) a given sequence of arguments SEQ. It follows that PARTCOMRELN also holds among (has the same value VAL for) any other sequence SEQ-PRIME obtainable from SEQ by permuting some or all of the odd-numbered members of SEQ while keeping all of its even-numbered members fixed.

Note that PARTCOMRELN must have an arity (see arity) of at least three and cannot be an instance of CommutativeRelation (as any instance of the latter is commutative in all of its argument-places).

Instances of PartiallyCommutativeRelation include pathsJoinAt, formsBorderBetween, and BlockOfStreetBetweenFn.

A specialization of both SoundInformationBearingThing and Artifact_Intangible. Each instance of Music is a particular sound produced by actions such as singing, whistling, playing an instrument, playing recorded music, and so on. Music has certain features that distinguish it from random noise (though recognizing them may depend upon a specific cultural background); such features usually include variations of pitch over time (i.e., melody), multiple (somehow) related pitches sounding at one time (i.e., some kind of harmony), and/or some regular temporal pattern to the component sounds (i.e., rhythm). Instances of Music include the debut performance of Beethoven's Fifth Symphony, Leonard Bernstein's rendition of the Ninth Symphony with the BPO in Berlin in 1989, a particular playing of a particular CD of Bernstein's 1989 Ninth in Berlin, and the Messiah sing-in in Austin, TX, in 1995. This collection is not to be confused with MusicalText or MusicalTextCopy (qq.v.), which refer to the represented instructions which musicians often follow in order to create Music.

comment: A collection of collections of collections of time-intervals. Each instance INTTYPETYPE of MutuallyDisjointIntervalCollectionType is a collection of interval-types INTTYPE(1), ..., INTTYPE(n) whose own instances are mutually temporally disjoint, in the sense that no instance of INTTYPE(i) temporally intersects any instance of INTTYPE(j) (for 1 <= i <= n; 1 <= j <= n; i =/ j). For example, DayOfWeekType (whose instances are Monday, Tuesday, etc.) is a MutuallyDisjointIntervalCollectionType, as no monday temporally intersects any tuesday or wednesday or ..., no tuesday temporally intersects any monday or wednesday or ..., and so on. An important specialization of MutuallyDisjointIntervalCollectionType is CyclicalSuccessiveIntervalGroupType (q.v.), each of whose instances is such that _its_ instances recur in a cyclic pattern that covers all of time. label: oriented location underspecified

comment:
The collection of locations, tangible or otherwise, which are
typically conceptualized by human beings for purposes of common-sense
reasoning as possessing some sense of 'vertical orientation'. Language is
permeated with metaphors based on such oriented states/abstract-locations,
as in 'He is high', 'I'm down', 'his spirits rose', 'mine fell', 'Ishtar
nose-dived', etc.  These states are thus very important for many inference
tasks that must reason about affective states.  Orientation metaphors are
amongst the most pervasive in any language, e.g.: Up = More = Good =
Desirable, Down = Less = Bad = Undesirable.

comment: The Missile_AIM_120 advanced medium-range air-to-air missile (AMRAAM) is a new generation air-to-air missile. The AMRAAM weighs 340 pounds and uses an advanced solid-fuel rocket motor to achieve a speed of Mach 4 and a range in excess of 30 miles. In long-range engagements AMRAAM heads for the target using inertial guidance and receives updated target information via data link from the launch aircraft. It transitions to a self-guiding terminal mode when the target is within range of its own monopulse radar set. The AIM-120 also has a "home-on-jam" guidance mode to counter electronic jamming. With its sophisticated avionics, high closing speed, and excellent end-game maneuverability, chances of escape from AMRAAM are minimal. Upon intercept an active-radar proximity fuze detonates the 40-pound high-explosive warhead to destroy the target. At closer ranges AMRAAM guides itself all the way using its own radar, freeing the launch aircraft to engage other targets.

label: path chain
PathChain
comment: A specialization of List. Each path chain is a List LIST = (X(1) Y(1) X(2) Y(2) ... X(n) Y(n) X(n+1)) satisfying the following conditions: (i) each X(k) is a Thing (q.v.) and each Y(k) is a Path_Generic (q.v.), i.e., the length of LIST is an odd number greater than 2, every even-numbered position in LIST is a Path_Generic, and every odd-numbered item is a Thing. (ii) Each Path_Generic in LIST joins the points just before and after it in LIST. That is to say, (iia) if the kth item PATH in LIST is a Path_Simple (q.v.), and if A is the (k-1)th item and B is the (k+1)th item in LIST, then (pathBetween PATH A B) holds, and (iib) if the kth item CYCLE is a Path_Cyclic (q.v.), and if A is the (k-1)th item and B is the (k+1)th item in LIST, then (pointOnCycle A CYCLE) holds and A = B. Note that the concatenation of all the paths (simple or cyclic) in such a list results in a Traversal (q.v.). For example, letting PATH1 and PATH2 be instances of Path_Simple and CYCLE a Path_Cyclic, if (pathBetween PATH1 A B), (pathBetween PATH2 B C) and (pointOnCycle C CYCLE), then (TheList A PATH1 B PATH2 C CYCLE C) is a PathChain. Note that although each instance of PathChain determines a unique instance of Traversal that is from X(1) to X(n+1), many different PathChains may determine the same Traversal.

label: modified Lambert conformal projection
ModifiedLambertConformalProjection
comment:
A specialization of SecantConicProjection whose instances are similar to ordinary LambertConformalProjections, but have been modified so as to be better suited for representing polar regions. These are also known as Ney's projections. Typically, when a conic projection is centered at a pole, the parallels are shown as arcs instead of circles, and the pole is shown as as arc instead of a point. In a ModifiedLambertConformalProjection, a parallel near the pole is chosen as its higher standard parallel; then a little "stretching" is done to complete the circles of the parallels and to eliminate the arc of the pole

A modified Lambert conformal projection is virtually conformal over its entire extent; but since not strictly a ConformalProjection it's not suited for highly accurate work.

A specialization of Translocation. Each instance of Movement_TranslationEvent is an event in which an object (an instance of SomethingExisting) moves some distance (so that at some point in the event, the object's center of mass changes location with respect to the relevant frame of reference). The moving object need not move completely out of its original spatial extent; for example, a building moving one foot to the left undergoes a Movement_TranslationEvent. Instances of Movement_TranslationEvent include events in which the movement ends in the same place it started from (e.g. one lap of a race car around the Indianapolis race track, or a trip to the grocery store and back). In such cases (all of which are instances of the specialization Translation_NoLocationChange), the to and from locations of the movement (see the predicates toLocation and fromLocation) are identical. In other cases of Movement_TranslationEvent (e.g. the movement of the baseball during a home run hit by Roger Maris), the to and from locations are different; in these cases, the movement events are also instances of Translation_LocationChange (q.v.).

label: null boundary

comment:
A specialization of #$NullSpaceRegion (q.v.). Each instance of NullBoundary is a null space region that is the (empty) boundary of a SpatiallyUnboundedThing (q.v.), according to a convention adopted in certain geometrical contexts. This convention is a simplifying assumption that allows a "boundary function" (the function from things in space to their boundaries; see boundaryOfSpatialThing) to be defined as a TotalFunction on the collection SpatialThing. At most one null boundary is recognized with respect to any given context.

Note that the dimensionality (see dimensionOfSpatialThing) of any null boundary is set by fiat to -1. This conforms with the OpenGISSimpleFeaturesSpecificationForSQL standard.

label: monitoring

comment: A specialization of PurposefulAction. Each instance of Monitoring is an event in which one or more agents keep track of some ongoing situation, such as the movement of a storm, a military operation, or a series of related crimes. Each instance of Monitoring has sub-events of two different types (see the predicate subEventTypes): the first type of sub-event is the establishment of communication links with relevant information sources, while the second type of sub-event is the gathering of information (see the collection InformationGathering) from these sources. Instances of these two types of event can occur any number of times in a given instance of Monitoring, although the first instance of the latter type must always be preceded by an instance of the former type. For example, in monitoring the movement of a storm, some agent may establish some communication link with a weather station acquiring information about the storm, and then gather information about the storm from the station. This could be repeated with different weather stations in the same instance of Monitoring, as long as the information gathered concerns the same storm.

comment: A collection of three disjoint collections, GovernmentalOrganization, QuasiGovernmentalOrganization and PrivateSectorOrganization. Each instance of OrganizationBySector is a set whose elements are distinguished by the sector in which the element Organizations operate. Instances of Organizations can be distinguished on the basis of whether they are governmental (e.g., FederalCommunicationsCommission), quasi-governmental (e.g., FederalHomeLoanMortgageCorporation), or private sector (e.g., IBMInc and SierraClub). This collection differs from OrganizationTypeByActivityType in that OrganizationTypeByActivityType segregates instances of Organization on the basis of the specific type of activity they engage in. For example, ResearchOrganization is an element of the collection of OrganizationTypeByActivityType, but not of OrganizationBySector. An instance of ResearchOrganization might be an instance of any of the collections, GovernmentalOrganization, QuasiGovernmentalOrganization, or PrivateSectorOrganization. This collection differs from OrganizationTypeByProfitMotive in that OrganizationTypeByProfitMotive segregates instances of Organization on the basis of whether or not they are motivated by the desire to make a profit for their owners.

NWSContentTest

Microscopist
october 2005 taxonomy demo individual

NaturalLanguage
non-powered device
NonPoweredDevice

Each instance of NonPoweredDevice is a device which does not need to have any kind of energy supplied to it in order for it to perform its intended function. Examples of NonPoweredDevices include tables, floor mats, bookshelves, shirts, and coat hangars. A hammer would not be an instance of NonPoweredDevice, since it requires kinetic energy to perform its intended function.

health provider national headquarters
NationalHeadquartersHealthProviderOrganization

label: the Machupo virus
Machupo-Virus
comment: A specialization of Virus. Machupo_Virus is the type of virus that causes instances of Machupo (Bolivian Hemorrhagic Fever).

A specialization of Informing, (AttemptingFn Lying), and Pretending. Each instance of Lying is an event in which the performer is not telling the truth, believes that what he is saying is not true, and intends to be saying what he says to get his audience to believe what he says.

Lying
Olympic Women's 4 By 100 Meter Medley Relay
OlympicWomensSwim-4By100MeterMedleyRelay

Microfiche

Navigator-Explorer
mixed forest (E1)
MidLatitudeMixedForest-E1

Each MidLatitudeMixedForest_E1 is a GeographicalRegion that is 5-25% covered with coniferous and deciduous trees, but where neither type of tree exceeds the other by 60% of all the trees present. The USArmyFieldManual5_33VegetationMapCode assigns MidLatitudeMixedForest_E1 a Vegetation Map Code of (E1).

Panting

Opener-Device

MetamorphicRock

PediatricCriticalCareSpecialist

NetworkPropagation

label: Medium Earth Orbit
MediumEarthOrbit
comment: Satellites in MediumEarthOrbit (MEO) orbit the earth at a height of 5,000 to 10,000 miles. MEO satellites cover much more of the earth's surface than satellites in LowEarthOrbit, but not as much of the Earths's surface as satellites in GeosynchronousEarthOrbit, and are often used in conjunction with satellites in GeosynchronousEarthOrbit. Because they orbit the Earth in a lower orbit than GEO satellites, MEO satellites offer clearer transmission and shorter transmission delay.

label: payment shock
PaymentShock
comment: The collection of all payment shocks. A type of HumanActivity.

label: microchannel thing
Microchannel

label: packed cyclifier lexicon specification
PackedCyclifierLexiconSpecification
comment: A specialization of CyclifierLexiconSpecification. Instances of PackedCyclifierLexiconSpecification will return semTrans semantics that will pack as much ambiguity as possible into a single lexical entry. For example, if the word "blork" has two denotations, #$Blork and #$Blonk, that fit in the same syntactic contexts, the lexical entry returned by a PackedCyclifierLexiconSpecification will be of the form (isa :NOUN (TheIntendedOneOfFn "blork" #$Blork #$Blonk)). This contrasts with a CyclifierLexiconSpecification, which would return two separate entries: (isa :NOUN #$Blork) and (isa :NOUN #$Blonk).

label: oil field equipment
OilFieldEquipment
comment: Miscellaneous equipment used during the development of an OilField. Includes the construction equipment, the specialized drilling apparatus, and everything else used during the construction.

label: water pathway
PathThroughWater
comment: The collection of all designated or customary Path_Spatials that go entirely through water (underwater). This would include designated undersea lanes for submarines, or corridors of fish migrations, etc. An object following such a path is immersed in, and supported by, the water. Thus it excludes a SolidSurfacePathThroughWater, and a WaterSurfacePath. For arbitrary trajectories of motions through water, use TrajectoryThroughWater.

Many, but not all of these organizations have 'transnational' scope; neither are all TransnationalCriminalOrganizations OrganizedCrimeOrganizations in the traditional sense.

MethylphosphonicDichloride

comment: A specialization of Organization. Each instance of MilitaryOrganization is an organization whose function (and expertise) is the use of armed force, or the threat of such use, against enemies, especially other organized, armed enemies. A military organization includes its fighting forces and their command structure, together with dedicated support services controlled by that military command. Typically, there are special conditions in the relationships between a MilitaryOrganization and its workers, going beyond what is expected in work agreements in civilian settings, including strict sanctions to enforce obedience. This collection includes GovernmentMilitaryOrganizations such as the armies, navies, and air forces of the world's governments, and in addition private armies, rebel armies, and organized mercenary units.

The soil commonly has a moderately low, or lower, saturated hydraulic conductivity within one meter of the surface, or periodically receives high rainfall, or both. (Field Book for Describing and Sampling Soils, U.S. Department of Agriculture)

comment: NetIncreasingFunction is function which shows a net increase in its value from 'start' to 'finish'. Such functions may take on any intermediate values so long as the net change in value from 'start' to 'finish' is positive. More formally, let x denote an element in the domain of some NetIncreasingFunction, F. Thus F(x) denotes an element in the range of F. Let x1 denote the lower bound on x. Let x2 denote the upper bound on x. F is an NetIncreasingFunction if and only if F(x1) < F(x2). See NetDecreasingFunction. See also MonotonicallyIncreasingFunction whose elements show an increase (technically, a non-decrease) for each successive range element.

A specialization of PhysicalEvent whose instances include translational or rotational movements of whole objects (see MovementEvent), objects changing shape (see ShapeChangeEvent), as well as events in which salient parts of an object move or change shape in relation to the reference frame of the whole object.

For example, although a ticking grandfather clock is not normally undergoing either a MovementEvent or a ShapeChangeEvent, it can still be said to be moving -- and thus undergoing a MovementOrShapeChangeEvent -- in virtue of the fact that a salient part of the clock, the pendulum, is swinging. (Of course, the pendulum itself is periodically undergoing Movement_Rotation, and the tip of the pendulum is undergoing a Movement_TranslationEvent.) As a negative example, a catatonic person should not be thought of as undergoing any MovementOrShapeChangeEvent. Although blood moves through such a person's veins, her lungs expand and contract, and so on, these things would not normally be considered salient enough to entail that the person herself was undergoing a movement or shape change event.

comment: The collection of all those MathematicalOrderings ORDER in which the ordering relation R is a reflexive, transitive and antisymmetric relation on the baseSet S of ORDER. R is reflexive on S if and only if for each X in S, R(X X). R is transitive on S if and only if for each X, Y and Z in S, R(X Y) and R(Y Z) imply R(X Z). R is antisymmetric on S if and only if for each X and Y in S, R(X Y) and R(Y X) imply X = Y. For example, if you take a set of Lists and take the subLists relation restricted to this set, then you have a PartialOrdering because the subLists relation is reflexive, transitive and antisymmetric. Since the ordering relation in each PartialOrdering is reflexive and transitive, the collection PartialOrdering is a subcollection of QuasiOrdering. Subcollections of PartialOrdering include TreeOrdering, TotalOrdering and Lattice_LatticeTheoretic. If you want a MathematicalOrdering in which the ordering relation is irreflexive, see PartialOrdering_Strict.

comment:
A specialization of Quantity (q.v.). This is the collection of quantities that have a numeric component and could actually be used to measure something, as opposed to (say) merely ranking it on a scale. Arithmetic operations (such as addition and multiplication) can be performed on measurable quantities, as they can on purely numeric scalars (see NumericInterval).

Specializations of MeasurableQuantity include Distance, Temperature, Mass, and Time_Quantity. Other, broader specializations are OneDimensionalQuantity, TwoDimensionalQuantity, and ThreeDimensionalQuantity.

Any quantity (that at least in principle could be) returned by a UnitOfMeasure (q.v.) function is a measurable quantity. In CycL, particular measurable quantities are usually represented as the result of applying a unit-of-measure function to a real number or pair of reals. For example, (Meter 5) is the distance 5 meters.

For predicates that relate things to measurable quantities that characterize them, see MeasurableQuantitySlot.

NonEmptyCollection
comment:
A collection of collections and a specialization of NonEmptySetOrCollection. A collection is an instance of NonEmptyCollection if and only if it has at least one instance.

Some collections, aguably, are by their very nature necessarily non-empty; e.g. Set_Mathematical. Conversely, some collections are non-empty in some contexts and empty in others; e.g. Horse is non-empty in the context of the present-day actual world but empty in certain counterfactual contexts in which horses never existed. Similarly, a TimeDependentCollection might be empty at certain times and non-empty at certain other times; e.g. the collection of female US presidents is currently empty but will hopefully become non-empty some time in the near future. This last example demonstrates that NonEmptyCollection is itself a time-dependent collection.

Note that each instance of NonEmptyCollection intersectsWith (q.v.) Thing.

Cf. EmptyCollection.

label: macro relation
MacroRelation
comment:
A specialization of Relation whose instances are used to form shorthand expressions for more complex formulas. Each instance of MacroRelation is correlated -- via an expansion assertion -- with a certain template for a class of (possibly quantified) CycL formulas. A closed formula (i.e. a closed "GAF" or "NAT"; see CycLClosedFormula) built from a given macro-relation is treated by the Cyc system as semantically equivalent to the (usually more complex) corresponding formula fitting the template. Thus suppose the macro-relation MACROREL had an expansion assertion of the form:

(expansion MACROREL COMPLEX-RELATIONAL-STRUCTURE :ARG1 ... :ARGN) .

Then a closed formula of the form

(MACROREL TERM(1) ... TERM(N))

would be treated by the system as shorthand for the more complex formula

(COMPLEX-RELATIONAL-STRUCTURE TERM(1) ... TERM(N)) .

Specializations of MacroRelation include RuleMacroPredicate, ELRelation, and TermMacroFunction (qq.v.). Instances of MacroRelation that are not in any of the latter three collections include implies, argFormat, and quotedIsa.

Each instance involves preparation events, and, in those cases where the prepartation events are successful, a rocket launch (see LaunchingARocket). label: partial denotational function

comment: A specialization of Function_Denotational whose instances are partial functions: functions that do not have well-defined values for everything to which they can legally be applied. More precisely, an (N-ary) function F is partial if it is undefined -- i.e. returns no value -- for one or more (length N sequences of) things that meet its (respective) argument-type constraints (see ArgTypePredicate). An example of a PartialFunction is TangentFn because although (Degree_UnitOfAngularMeasure 90) and (Degree_UnitOfAngularMeasure 270) both meet its argument-constraints, TangentFn is undefined for both. Another example of a PartialFunction is BorderBetweenFn. As the arg1Isa and arg2Isa for this binary function are both GeographicalRegion (and there are no further-restricting arg[N]Genl constraints on the function), BorderBetweenFn can be applied to any pair of geographical regions whatsoever. But of course not all pairs of regions are such that they share a border. Thus it is correct to assert, for example, (undefined (BorderBetweenFn Albania UnitedStatesOfAmerica)). Instances of Function_Denotational that are not partial are TotalFunctions.

label: one dimensional quantity

comment:
A specialization of MeasurableQuantity (q.v.). Each instance of OneDimensionalQuantity is a measurable quantity that is not defined in terms of (i.e. as the product or ratio of) other quantities. For example, (Mile 65) and (HoursDuration 1) are both instances of OneDimensionalQuantity; but (MilesPerHour 65), derived by dividing the former quantity by the latter, is not (cf. MultiDimensionalQuantity).

Specializations of OneDimensionalQuantity include Distance, Mass, and Time_Quantity.

Each one-dimensional quantity is equal to the result of applying some OneDimensionalUnitOfMeasure (q.v.) to some number or other NumericInterval (or pair of such intervals). If a OneDimensionalQuantity is multiplied or divided by a numeric-interval, the result is still a one-dimensional quantity; if two one-dimensional quantities that are numericallyComparable (q.v.) are added or subtracted, the result is still a one-dimensional quantity. Conversely, whenever one OneDimensionalQuantity is multiplied or divided by another OneDimensionalQuantity, the result is a TwoDimensionalQuantity. Two quantities that are not numerically-comparable cannot be added to or substracted from each other. And when a OneDimensionalQuantity is multiplied or divided by (or divides) a TwoDimensionalQuantity, the result is in many cases a ThreeDimensionalQuantity (q.v.).

See also PrimitiveOrderedQuantityType and FundamentalUnitType.

label: strict partial order

comment: The collection of all MathematicalOrderings ORDER in which the ordering relation R is an irreflexive and transitive relation on the baseSet S of ORDER, i.e., for each X in S, R(X X) does not hold, and for each X, Y and Z in S, R(X Y) and R(Y Z) imply R(X Z). For example, if one takes the set of all people, and the relation '__ is older than ...' on this set, one gets a PartialOrdering_Strict, since the relation '__ is older than ...' is irreflexive and transitive on this set. Note that the important difference between a PartialOrdering (q.v.) and a PartialOrdering_Strict is that the ordering relation of the former is reflexive, while that of the latter is irreflexive. Note also that the ordering relation R of a PartialOrdering_Strict ORDER is in fact antisymmetric (i.e., for each X and Y in S, R(X Y) and R(Y X) imply X = Y) and asymmetric (i.e., for each X and Y in S, R(X Y) and R(Y X) can never be both true) on the baseSet S. This is because both antisymmetry and asymmetry follow from transitivity and irreflexivity.

A specialization of AspatialInformationStore and AbstractIndividual (qq.v.). Each instance of Microtheory is an atemporal, aspatial, informational thing that represents a context in Cyc. Each microtheory (or 'mt') serves to group a set of assertions together that share some common assumptions; the assertions in an mt constitute the content of that mt. Note that each assertion in the Cyc knowledge base must be explicitly stated to be true in at least one microtheory. Assertions stated to be true in one mt will also be true (by inference) in more specialized mts that depend on the content of that mt. For example, if something is true in the HumanSocialLifeMt (q.v.), then it should by default be true in the more specialized UnitedStatesSocialLifeMt (q.v.). Specialized microtheories are related to the more general microtheories on which they depend by the predicate genlMt (q.v.). Note that every query is made in some mt, and the answer one gets to a query depends on the mt in which it is asked, since the only assertions which can be used to answer a query in an mt are those explicitly stated to be true in that mt, or in some more general mt. See also the predicate ist, which is used to relate an assertion to the microtheories in which it is true.

comment:
The collection of all collections that are "object-like" in at least one respect. A collection COL is object-like just in case there is some sense of 'part' according to which any (or nearly any) given proper part of an instance of COL is not itself an instance of COL; when this happens COL is said to be object-like with respect to that sense of 'part'.

More precisely, for a collection COL to be an instance of ObjectType it is sufficient that there be some specialization PARTPRED of properParts such that, for any OBJ1 and OBJ2, if (isa OBJ1 COL) and (PARTPRED OBJ1 OBJ2) both hold, then (isa OBJ2 COL) does not hold. (Also sufficient for COL's being an object-type is that there be some specialization INVPARTPRED of the inverse of properParts (see genlInverse) such that (INVPARTPRED OBJ2 OBJ1), with everything else remaining the same as above.) Note that neither of the above sufficient conditions for COL's being an object-type is strictly necessary: some exceptions are allowed. Thus as long as either one of the above conditionals holds in nearly all cases, COL should be considered an instance of ObjectType.

Here are two examples. Consider Automobile. Take an instance of that, say my car. Now consider one of the proper physicalParts of my car, say the steering wheel. The steering wheel is not an instance of Automobile. And the same would be true for any proper physical part of any car. So Automobile is an ObjectType. Consider CalendarYear. No proper timeSlices of a year is itself a year. So CalendarYear is an ObjectType.

See StuffType for the contrasting (though not disjoint) notion of being stuff-like.

Solid instances of Metal have a shiny luster, and are highly malleable. Specializations of Metal include Mercury, Potassium, Brass, Lead, and Iron.

comment: A type of map projection and a specialization of both CylindricalProjection and EquatorialProjection (qq.v.). Each instance of MercatorProjection involves projecting a Spheroid onto a cylinder (see CylindricalSurface_WithoutTopAndBottom) that is tangent with the spheroid along the equator (see equatorOfSpheroid). The projection is such that rhumb lines appear as straight lines, and their directions can be measured directly in the map. Both meridians and parallels are expanded at a ratio equal to the secant of the latitude (with a minor correction made for the oblate-spheroidal shape of the Earth's surface); since the secant of 90 degrees is infinity, the poles cannot be shown.

official record

comment: A collection of InformationBearingObjects. Each element of OfficialRecord is a record of some agent and exists for a particular purpose. For example, PersonnelRecord may contain employee information and other facts that are pertinent to the functioning of a business. OfficialRecords are typically issued and generated by institutions and they are held to a higher degree of veracity and authenticity than a mere collection of data. For example, official financial records are 'official' enough to be used to file taxes, request a loan, or appear as evidence in a court of law. There is an important distinction between OfficialDocument and OfficialRecord. An OfficialRecord may record the the number of passports issued to whom and on which date, but the OfficialDocument is the passport itself. In the same sense, a list of transactions for a business on a particular day is an OfficialRecord, the credit card receipts and tickets of sale are OfficialDocuments. One should read the comment for OfficialReport as a third distinction.

A collection of things that are paths or can be considered paths. Each Path_Generic is either a a non-self-crossing path (see Path_Simple) or a cycle (see Path_Cyclic). A Path_Generic may be spatio-temporally abstract (e.g. links in Graph Theory; see Multigraph), spatially-located but intangible (e.g. a LatitudeLine might be used as a path in some system; see Path_Spatial and its specializations), or fully concrete (such as a road, railroad, sea-lane, cowpath, pipe, blood vessel, fiber, or wire; see Path_Customary and PathArtifact). Path_Generic includes anything that is used as a path in some PathSystem (q.v.). If a Path_Generic is a Path_Customary, then it might or might not have a specified PathSystem in which it is a path; if the Path_Generic is not a Path_Customary, then it can only be a path in some given PathSystem. For example, an orange is not a customary path, but it can be a path for ants in a specified ant path system. For any Path_Generic, there can be a Traversal (q.v.) of something moving along the entirety of that path (and a single Traversal can cross itself, double back along itself, or go back and forth along some part of a Path_Generic any number of times.) Note that Path_Generic is _not_ a subcollection of Individual, because there is nothing in principle to prevent a mathematical set or a collection from being "used as a path" in some path system. For similar reasons, few if any (non-empty) collections or sets can definitively be considered disjoint with Path_Generic.

Each instance NIC of NonInitialCollection is a collection such that nothing can be an instance of NIC at the start of the thing's existence. Thus nothing can be an instance of NIC for its entire existence. Instanceship in NIC is typically "acquired" at some point in time T after the would-be instance INST comes into existence, where T might occur either during or after INST's existence (i.e. "posthumously"). comment:
A specialization of MilitaryOrganization. Each instance of ParamilitaryOrganization is an organization formed according to a military structure, but not as a part of any mainstream military force. Paramilitary organizations sometimes operate as auxiliaries to or in place of mainstream military forces (e.g. as border patrols or police units), but generally they operate independently of any government or national allegiance, often with loyalty to some political program or party.

Examples of ParamilitaryOrganizations include the MilitiaOfMontana and the Ulster Defence Association (UDA), the Protestant militant group operating in Northern Ireland.

label: monadic microtheory

comment: A MonadicMicrotheory is a temporally and otherwise unqualified Microtheory; it is indivisible along all currently defined microtheory dimensions (see MtSpace and MtDim). For example, PeopleDataMt is a MonadicMicrotheory, but (MtSpace PeopleDataMt) is not; nor is (MtSpace PeopleDataMt (MtDim mtTimeIndex (YearFn 1955))). Note, however, that a MonadicMicrotheory need not be atomic: (MtOfBeliefSystemFn Buddhism) is a MonadicMicrotheory. Together with PolyadicMicrotheory, this partitions Microtheory.
